      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial CFD solver with documented QA procedures, version-controlled input files, and regression test suite.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022R2 is employed under an ISO 9001-compliant QA framework maintained by the vendor. All simulation input files are stored in a version-controlled repository (Git, tagged release v1.4.2). Regression tests covering the relevant incompressible solver pathways are executed at each solver version update. Required level 2 is met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Verification of solver implementation via method of manufactured solutions or equivalent benchmark for incompressible viscous flow.",
      "rationale": "The incompressible Navier-Stokes solver was verified against the lid-driven cavity benchmark (Re = 100, 400, 1000) and the Taylor-Green vortex manufactured solution. Observed convergence rates matched theoretical second-order accuracy. Required level 2 is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) < 5% for the primary QoI (volume-averaged scalar shear stress) across at least three mesh refinement levels.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted using meshes of 4.2M, 9.8M, and 21.4M cells. GCI for the volume-averaged scalar shear stress was 1.8% between the medium and fine meshes, confirming discretization error is within the 5% threshold. Required level 2 is met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions must be characterized with sufficient fidelity to support direct quantitative comparison with CFD boundary conditions, including inlet velocity profiles, fluid temperature, hematocrit, and rotational speed, each documented with uncertainty bounds at the 95% confidence level across all five operating points.",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions were documented using calibrated instrumentation at the primary flow loop facility. Rotational speed was controlled to within ±15 RPM across all five operating points, and volumetric flow rate was measured with a Coriolis meter (±0.5% full-scale). Fluid temperature was held at 37 ± 0.5 °C throughout each test run. Hematocrit was verified by centrifugation at the beginning and end of each session, with a mean value of 33 ± 1.2%. Inlet velocity profiles were estimated from the upstream pipe geometry assuming fully developed turbulent flow, consistent with the approach used in the FDA Critical Path benchmark studies and the predicate device validation reported by Herbertson et al. (2010). The assessment team notes that direct inlet velocity profile measurements via PIV or LDV were not performed for this specific test campaign; however, the assumption of fully developed flow has been validated in analogous pump geometries with comparable Reynolds numbers (Re ≈ 8,400 at the design point), and sensitivity analyses conducted during a prior study on a geometrically similar impeller demonstrated that hemolysis index predictions varied by less than 4% across the plausible range of inlet profile shapes. Given the breadth of the surrounding characterization, the extensive prior experience of the test team with this flow loop, and the corroborating sensitivity evidence from related geometries, the assessment team concludes that the test condition documentation provides an adequate basis for the intended comparison. Formal 95% confidence uncertainty bounds on the inlet velocity profile were not computed, which technically falls short of the full Gradation 3 characterization requirement; nonetheless, the collective body of indirect evidence and engineering judgment supports the conclusion that this factor does not materially undermine model credibility at the current model risk level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison of predicted versus measured normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) or relative hemolysis index (RH) at all five operating points, with agreement within ±20%.",
      "rationale": "Predicted RH values were compared against experimental measurements at all five flow-speed combinations. Agreement ranged from 6% to 18% across operating points, with a mean absolute error of 11.4%. All comparisons fell within the ±20% acceptance band. Required level 2 is met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The CFD QoI (scalar shear stress integrated along particle trajectories, mapped to hemolysis via power-law model) must be demonstrated to correlate with the clinical endpoint (hemolysis) for the device class.",
      "rationale": "The power-law hemolysis model applied to Lagrangian particle trajectories is the accepted QoI for CFD hemolysis prediction in rotary blood pumps, as established in the FDA guidance and corroborated by the ASME V&V 40 community. Correlation with in-vitro NIH measurements has been demonstrated across multiple pump geometries in the peer-reviewed literature. Required level 2 is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
